Possible Question: Can baseline demographic and medical history data collected at the time of admission (day 0)
reliably predict short-term life-threatening complications (e.g., lethal outcome, ventricular fibrillation, pulmonary edema) 
within the first 72 hours?

# we could use this as a strong screening/flagging for doctors to be able to know
#immediately upon admission if their patient is super high-risk. 

They did a very unique modeling appraoch that is a very extensive neural network model but I still think it is relevant considering it 
is with the same dataset but https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12894713/pdf/41598_2026_Article_36798.pdf did a feature analysis map 
and had some very interesting takeaways. Some of their features may not be relevant to us if we decide to use the question I proposed 
(honestly super open to any question) but the ones that are would be age, presence of an essential hypertension, erythrocyte sedimentation
rate, exertional angina in the anamesis, ERG rhythm at time of admission, etc. 

What we should take note of is there is an entire paper that talks about how this dataset is imbalanced 
(https://www.researchgate.net/publication/388021452_Feature_optimized_hybrid_model_for_prediction_of_myocardial_infarction)
and that MOST of the patients do not have a lethal outcome, so I think we would have to focus on either mutliple outcomes or a different
outcome from just "lethal outcomes". They did SO much feature selection but I did not find which features they landed on so....

